    <item>
      <title>Updating an Debian/Ubuntu OS that is no longer supported</title>
      <link>https://ismael.casimpan.com/quicktasks/post/upgrading-unsupported-debian-os/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Sep 2019 00:20:25 +0800</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://ismael.casimpan.com/quicktasks/post/upgrading-unsupported-debian-os/</guid>
      <description>
        
          
            In our example, we have Debian Squeeze (6.0) and it&#39;s been unsupported since Feb 2016. We can no longer install nor update the packages until you point it to another source...the archives.
So, in /etc/apt/sources.list, add you will see:
1deb http://ftp.us.debian.org/debian/ squeeze main 2deb-src http://ftp.us.debian.org/debian/ squeeze main Replace it with:
1deb http://archive.debian.org/debian squeeze main 2deb http://archive.debian.org/debian squeeze-lts main and you can now access &#39;apt-get&#39; or &#39;dpkg&#39; as before (but limited to what&#39;s in the archive).
          
          
        
      </description>
    </item>
    
